The San Francisco-based company is under pressure to persuade the advertising industry that they need to pay for advertising on Twitter, rather than simply using the social network as a free platform for PR. Twitter has more than 200m users who collectively send more than 400m tweets a day, but it has sometimes struggled to monetise them effectively. It has stepped up efforts over the past two years, with the introduction of a few different advertising products, but it now faces unpreceneted pressure to demonstrate that it can persuade companies to pay for ads on Twitter, without bombarding users with ads in a way that will alienate them. Twitter’s S-1, filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission ahead of the IPO, will remain sealed until early next month, but analysts estmate that the company will clock up more than $500m in revenues this year and double that figure in 2014. Digital Media
